{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_noone_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600258/1930020201/0577.xml":{"full_text":"C-6\nPRICES ARE STEADY\nON D. ([EXCHANGE\n[Thrift Grips Residents of the\nCapital\u2014Business Shows\nSigns of Improving.\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nPrices closed the week firm on the\nWashington Stock Exchange and with\na somewhat larger turnover. The final\nsale in Capital Traction was 10 shares\nat 89 after an earlier sale at 90 Vi.\nPotomac Electric Power 6 per cent pre\nferred wound up the week at 111 and\nthe last sale in Peoples Drug Stores\npreferred was made at 104.\nTwenty-five shares of Real Estate\nMortgage Sc Guaranty preferred came\nout at 7% and Terminal Refrigeration\nl Warehousing Corporation preferred\nI moved at 50. One hundred shares of\nFiremen's Insurance Co. sold at 41.\nTwenty shares of Mergenthaler came\nout at 107.\nIn the bond division, Washington\nGas Cs, series A, sold at 102 Vi- There\nI was a SI,OOO sale in Washington Rail\nway Electric 4s at 83 Vi and another\nfI,OOO transaction at 83%.\nIn the unlisted department 25 shares\nof Park Savings Bank stock changed\nhands at 78. The other unlisted securi\nties were called off and showed very few\nprice changes from last week.\nOne of the most important events in\nfinancial Washington during the coming\nweek is the annual meeting of the\nWashington Gas Light Co. So far as\ncan be learned in advance, Ord Preston\nwill be returned to the presidency when\nthe directors organize for the year. At\nthis time last year there was intense\nrivalry over control of the company,\n*ow in the hands of outside interest.\nFine Christmas Club Record.\nIt is a remarkable record that the\nChristmas Savings' Clubs in Washing-,\nton have made in the past few years.\nThe report just announced that the\nclubs again this year have grown sub\nstantially in numbers and funds sub\nscribed was received with great satis\nfaction by local bankers. Records of\npast performances are highly interest\ning, the figures since 1925 being as\nfollows:\nYear. Members. Amount Subscribed.\n1924 49,385 $3,000,000\n1925 66,279 4,747,741\n1926 73,615 5,544,976\n1927 78,145 5,994,903\n1928 83,178 7,046,497\n1929 87,701 7,462,079\n1930 91,430 7,772,273\nThus it will be seen that in seven\nyears the number of accounts has\njumped from under 50,000 to well toward\n100,000. At the same time the amount\nsubscribed has increased by leaps and\nbounds from $3,00,000 to $7,772,273\nIt is only natural that banks from\nau over the country have written to\nWashington to find out what makes the\nChristmas clubs here so popular. In his\nannual report at Montauk Beach last\nJune, Eliot H. Thomson, chairman of\nthe District Bankers\u2019 Association ad\nvertising committee, announced the re\nceipt of a great many inquiries.\nBusiness Turning Upward.\nIn many respects the year began on\na more auspicious basis than did 1929,\nsays the First National Bank of Boston.\nFunds for business purposes are avail\nable on more reasonable terms. As a\nmatter of fact, the whole world credit\nsituation is on a sounder basis, and as\na consequence, world trade relations\nshould be more satisfactory.\nThe farm situation is in a somewhat\nstronger position. Estimated farm in\ncome for the year ended June 30, 1929,\nis above that of the preceding year.\nBuilding prospects are brighter than a\nyear ago. Aggregate contracts awarded\nfor the coming year should make a\nfavorable showing compared with 1929.\nOs much significance is the decided\ntrend toward co-operation among vari\nous members of the trade and Industry\nto maintain stabilized conditions in\nboth prices and production.\nHand-to-mouth buying continues to\nbe an important factor in keeping trade\non a fairly even keel. But of more sig\nnificance than all these factors is the\nstrong underlying force of American\nprogress which carries our business ac\ntivities steadily forward. The present\nrecession is merely a temporary inter\nruption in the general upward move\nment.\nFranklin Bank Looks Ahead.\nThe Franklin National Bank, in its\nFebruary business outlook, predicts that\nthe income of the people of the United\nStates will approach $95,000,000,000 in\n1929 when the totals have beenr as\nsembled.\nAccumulating data covering business\noperations in 1929 reveal a notable list\nof new records established during the\nyear, despite the drop in general activity\nwhich came in the closing months.\nOutstanding among the new marks\nreported are: Automobile output, 23\nper cent above the best previous year;\nsteel production, up 10 per cent; bank\ndebits, 7 per cent; retail trade, 3 per\ncent; electricity output, 12 per cent; life\ninsurance sales, 11 per cent, and busi\nness profits, 19 per cent.\nFigures compiled by the Federal Re\nserve Bank of New York covering 161\nseries of data give the aggregate of the\nNation\u2019s business as 4 per cent larger\nin 1929 than in 1928, the previous high\nyear, and approximately 15 per cent\nabove the 1923-1925 average.\nHow great will be the extent of the\ncurrent recession from this high level\nof activity, and its probable duration,\nare questions which still occupy the\nforeground of interest.\nA summary of the general situation\nas it presents itself at the close of the\nfirst month tends to confirm President\nHoover\u2019s view that 1930 will prove a\ngood average year, with business hold\ning its own, with some exceptions in\nthe first six months, and possibly mov\ning to some new marks in the last six\nmonths.\nGleaned in Financial District.\nWashington cleared $22,890,000 this\nweek against $27,018,000 last week,\nwhich is a decrease of 34.4 from the\ncorresponding week in 1929.\nEnrollments at Washington Chapter,\nAmerican Institute of Banking, for the\nsecond semester have reached 240,\nmaking the number of bankers in all\nclasses for the year 625. This will be\nincreased during the next few days,\nenrollments closing February 10. The\nchapter students will be taken on an\neducational tour through the offices of\nthe Chesapeake Sc Potomac Telephone\nCo. next Wednesday evening.\nMore than 2,400 employes of Childs\nCo. purchased the company\u2019s common\nstock at $56 a share under the install\nment purchase plan expiring February\n1, according to L. E. Buswell, treasurer\nof the company. Childs Co. has about\n10,000 employes.\nThere was a last-minute rush to sub\nscribe, several hundred additional sub\nscriptions being received on the closing\nday. Childs common closed at 62% on\nthe stock exchange yesterday.\nGERMAN FIRM GRANTED\n$32,500,000 BANK LOAN\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, February I.\u2014A loan of\napproximately $32,500,000 for Siemens\nSc Halske of Germany, parent company\nof the Siemens electrical equipment\nmanufacturing group, was announced\ntoday by Dillon, Read Sc Co. The issue\nis to be in long-term partiepating de\nbentures, which are to be publicly of\nfered early next week. Wall Street un\nderstands, however, that the General\nElectric Co. is to take virtually the\n\u2022ntire issue, giving the American con\ncern an Interest in the largest electri\ncal company of Europe.\nPrevious American financing for\nSiemens Sc Halske includes a $24,000,000\nIssue In 1922 and a $12,000,000 loan in\nwt, r\nI FINANCIAL\nRe-Elected\nCLARENCE A. ASPINWALL,\nWho has Just been re-elected president\nof the Security Storage Co. The an\nnual report to the stockholders, pre\nsented during the past week, showed\nan excellent business in 1929.\nI\nNEW BOND ISSUES\nTO BE READY SOON\nRailroad Offerings Head List\nof Securities Planned in\nNear Future.\nNEW YORK, February I.\u2014From the\nstandpoint of price improvement the\npast week has been negative in the in\nvestment market.\nThere has been some marking down\nof municipals, some small declines in\noutstanding issues affected by new ones\nbrought out at attractive levels and\nsome restlessness on the part of the in\nvesting public due to the small yield of\nhigh-grade bonds. This latter factor is\nevidenced in a point decline in the aver\nage price of 10 of the highest types of\nbonds, and declines ranging from y 2 to\n2 points in United States Government\nloans.\nThe week saw the cessation, to a large\ndegree, of the transferring from out\nstanding bonds to new Issues. Most of\nthe issues left on the shelves of dealers\nhave been distributed. There is still\nevidence that some of the recent offer\nings have been coming back into the\nmarket. But this practice is dwindling.\nHowever, any general advance in bond\nlevels must be some distance off as yet\nbecause of the large amount of new\nfinancing still in prospect.\nNew Bond Issues.\nNew bond issues totaled about $130,-\n000,000, against $79,394,000 last week.\nThis compares with the total of $305,-\n000,000 in a recent week. One interest\ning point was that the end of January\nshowed a renewed tendency toward\nstock financing. The Republic Iron Sc\nSteel merger was accomplished without\na bond issue. The Insull utilities group\nis planning $50,000,000 stock financing.\nMany other concerns issued additional\nstock by issue of \u201crights.\u201d In the same\nweek of 1929 the total of stock financing\nwas double that of bonds.\nThere is much bond financing in\nprospect, including $32,000,000 by the\nCleveland, Cincinnati, Chicago Sc St.\nLouis Railroad; $26,000,000 by the\nDelaware, Lackawanna Sc Western;\n$18,000,000, Cleveland Union Terminal,\nand numerous equipment issues. The\nlatter are incidental to activity among\nequipment manufacturers, which is at\npresent on an upward swing. San\nFrancisco proposes to float a $60,000,-\n000 loan for the purpose of purchasing\nthe properties in San Francisco of the\nPacific Gas Electric Co. and the\nGreat Western Power Co.\nIncreased firmness in stocks during\nthe week had its direct effect on the\nbond market in a substantially higher\nrange of prices for convertible issues\nand other bonds having stock warrants\nor bonus features. In an indirect way,\nit aided bonds that are dependent on\nthe earnings of the companies putting\nthem out. For instance, 10 of the lowest\ngrade bonds listed on the stock and\ncurb exchanges are currently at their\nhighest levels for the year, and an\naverage of 10 points above their low\nlevels of this same month. This, of\ncourse, points to speculative operations.\nMost of this group are bonds selling\nbelow 50 or, in other words, on a re\nceivership basis.\nForeign Dollar Bonds.\nIn the list of foreign dollar bonds,\nit is interesting to note that a group of\n10 low-grade foreign bonds is at an\naverage price more than five points\nabove the low levels touched early in\nthe month. This is probably attributa\nble to buying for foreign account.\nOne thing that has helped bonds,\nand is no doubt the reason why high\ngrada issues have not declined as they\nmay well have been expected to do in\nthe face of so many new offerings of\nfered at discounts, is the general de\ncline of commodity prices the world\nover. To the man who holds bonds\nand has, consequently, a fixed Income,\nthis lowering of commodity prices,\nof rents, and everything else, is equiva\nlent to an increase in salary, while\nat the same time it means smaller\ndividends to the owner of equities and\nsmaller profits to the man who is in\nbusiness for himself.\nReductions in the prices of muncipal\nissues were blamed partly on the Chi\ncago situation, which came to a crisis\nduring the week. However, the Sani\ntary District was able to borrow enough\n\u2014at a high rate of interest\u2014 to pay the\ncoupons on its bonds, which are due\nshortly.\nThe market for foreign loans has\ngone ahead day by day. French, Bel\ngian, Japanese and British dollar credits\nwere outstandingly strong. South Amer\nican issues gained a little, although they\nare still a long way behind the rest of\nthis section in their recovery from last\nyear\u2019s low level. Argentine descriptions\nwere favorably affected by the anounce\nment that the gold conversion office\nmay shortly be reopened by President\nIrlgoyen, and also by the report that an\nattempt is to be made to re-establish\nthe peso.\n(Copyright, 1930.)\nINVESTMENT BANKERS\nELECT GOVERNORS\nSpecial Dispatch to The Btar.\nCHICAGO, February I.\u2014Election of\nthree governors to All vacancies on the\nboard of governors of the Investment\nBankers\u2019 Association of America was\nannounced today by Trowbridge Cal\nlaway, president. The new govern\nors are Frank McNair, Harris Trust\nand Savings Bank, Chicago; Ralph For\ndon, Guardian Detroit Co., Inc., De\ntroit, and Canton O'Donnell, O'Donnell-\nOwen Sc Co., Denver.\n\nTakes Up Bond Issue.\nRICHMOND, Va., February 1 (Spe\ncial). \u2014After all bids had been turned\ndown because they did not offer enough,\nWlstar H. Embrey became the pur\nchaser of $50,000 of Fredericksburg,\nVa., city bonds. Mr. Embrey Is a citizen\nof Fredericksburg and former police\njustice, but is not In the banking or\nbond business.\nEmbrey bought the bonds at face\nvalue at an interest rate of 4% per\nfieol.\nthe SUNDAY STAB, WASHINGTON. D. C\u201e FEBRUARY 2. 1930\u2014PART ONE.\nRESALE PRICE Bill\nAROUSESINTEREST\nMeasure Designed to Aid Re\ntailers by Restoring Lib\nerty of Contract.\nBY J. C. ROYLE.\nHiir r swvL2L the resale price\nm y re6ult in drastic\nf. tl i ar ?f CS .r\u00b0 f i .^n Cy wlth regard to many\nft\u2122** merchandising. This\nnirt/.rfbiJ 1 th^ S J low been favorably re-\nE Ho ls committee on in-\nf \u00b0r e, k n commerce, would\nrestore liberty of contract between pro\nducers of trade marked or branded\n\u00abo\u00bb>BOdttta9\u00abril Bi\u00dftelta. to the effect\nthat the distributor will not resell the\nSX the 6 producer. PriC tipU\nThis has been a bone of contention\nbetween producers and distributors. In-\nI to this have come the chain stores and\ndepartment stores, which handle manv\narticles other than those brilfded o?\nt trade marked. Some of these dlstribu\ntors have followed a policy of selling\nmarked or branded articles below the\nl price fixed by the manufacturer in order\nto attract customers who would in their\nvisit to the store purchase other arti\ncles.\nQuestion of Profit.\nThe question of profit on the branded\narticles in many cases was not a fac\ntor. In some Instances, such articles\nhave been sold at below cost to the dis\ntributor. In these cases the latter sim\nply charged up the loss to sales promo-\nI tlon or advertising expense.\nThe practice was the cause of the\nbitter trade war which has raged in\nthe retail cigarette lines. Chain gro\nceries, department stores, drug stores\nand cigar store chains have slashed\nprices until in some instances the\namount received was less than cast of\nthe article. The manufacturers of the\nbetter known brands of cigarettes fixed\nthe wholesale price at $6.40 a thousand\nRetailers in New York City have sold\nthese brands as low as $3.95 a thousand,\na loss, if both figures are correct, of\n$2.45 a thousand.\nAs long as the manufacturers receive\n$6.40 a thousand they are not affected,\nbut the distributors, who would not or\ncould not cut their profit margins close\nto or under the cost price, have com\nplained bitterly. The same situation ex\nists in a score of trade-marked and na\ntionally advertised articles.\nRepresentative Clyde Kelly of Pitts\nburgh is the sponsor of the bill just\nfavorably reported by the House com\nmittee. Mr. Kelly said today:\n\u201cThe action of the interstate and for\neign commerce committee in favorably\nreporting the Capper-Kelly fair trade\nbill is gratifying to all believers of fair\ncompetition in business. It is proof of\nthe justice of the contention urged\nthrough many years that predatory\nprice-cutters shall not be permitted to\ndestroy standard quality goods and in\ndependent distributors through cut\nthroat practices. There can be no doubt\nas to final success in the effort to se\ncure a square deal to independent Amer\nican business.\u201d\nMeasure Meets Opposition.\nDistributors who oppose the measure\ndeclare that no one has the right to\ndetermine for any American the price\nat which he shall sell what he owns.\nIn connection with this phase of the\nargument, the report of the House com\nmittee concludes:\n\u201cAnd finally, and perhaps most im\nportant for the public welfare, the ef\nfect of this bill would be to put the\nsmall local dealers more nearly on a\ncompetitive basis with the great chain\nstore and other combinations. It is\ngenerally and properly recognized that\nthe gradual extinction of small inde\npendent dealers would be a loss to\ncountless communities throughout the\nNation and so to the Nation itself. A\nsmall independent dealer, who is identi\nfied with the community where his store\nexists, and who is active in its life as\na citizen and taxpayer, is surely more\nadvantageous to that community than\na mere selling agency of a foreign con\ncern.\u201d\n(Copyright, 1930.)\nWHEAT PRICES GAIN\nON ACREAGE REPORT\nAdvances at Liverpool Reflected\nin Further Recovery at\nChicago.\nB; the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, February I.\u2014Wheat rose\nin price here today to 4 cents above yes\nterday\u2019s bottom figures. The rally was\nlargely due to sharp advances in wheat\nquotations at Liverpool, where higher\nprices on wheat offerings from Argen\ntina were a factor and where some im\nprovement of European continental de\nmand for wheat was reported. An au\nthoritative unofficial estimate Issued in\nChicago today Indicated 1.1 per cent\nreduction of World\u2019s Winter wheat acre\nage. compared with a year ago.\nWheat closed unsettled, 1% to l%a\nV/b bushel higher than yesterday\u2019s\nfinish. Corn closed 1%a% to up,\noats l 2 to %a% advanced, and provi\nsions showing gains ranging from a\nshade to 15.\nWHEAT\u2014 High. Low. Close.\nMarch 1.17% 1.16% 1.17%\nMay 1.32'/a 1.31% 1.22 V,\nJuly 1.24% 1.23% 1.34\nSeptember 1.27 1.25% 1.26V*\nMarch TV. 88 .87% .87Va\nMay 91% .90% .91V,\nJuly 93% .93V, .93%\nSeptember 93% .93% .93%\nOATS\u2014\nMarch 44V, .44'/, .44%\nMay 46 .45'/, .45%\nJuly 44% .44% .44%\nRYE\u2014\nMarch 87 .85% .86%\nMay 87V, .85% .87\nJuly 87% .86V, .87%\nSeptember 89V, .88'/, .89V,\nLARD\u2014\nMarch 10.45\nMay 10.65 10.60 10.82\nJuly 10.82 10.82 10.82\ncottonTshigher\nON TRADE BUYING\nWeek Xnd Covering Movement\nAlso Aids Market\u2014Close\nIs Steady.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, February I.\u2014The cot\nton market was higher today on week\nend covering and trade buying accom\npanied by talk of a firmer technical\nposition and encouraged by the some\nwhat steadier tone of Liverpool. May\ncontracts sold up to 16.66, making a\nnet advance of 23 points and a recovery\nof 29 points from the low level of yes\nterday, but reacted slightly under rea\nlizing and closed at 16.59. The general\nmarket closed steady at net advances\nof 12 to 15 points.\nFutures closed steady, 12 to 15 points\nhigher; March. 16.37a16.38; May, 16.59a\n16.80; July, 16.82a16.83; October, 17.02a\n17.03; December, 17.05; spot steady;\nmiddling, 16.50.\nOpening High Low Close\nMarch 18.23 16.40 16.23 18.37\nMay 18.50 16.66 16.48 18.59\nJuly 16.75 16.80 18.73 16.82\nl October 16.03 17.08 18.91 17.02\nDecember 17.03 17.20 17.03 17.15\n\nPENDER DIVIDEND.\nDirectors of David Pender Grocery\nCo., which has many stores in Virginia,\nhave declared the regular quarterly dlv\ni idend of 87'A cents per share on the\nclass A stock, payable March 1 to\natockhoiden at itcoid Peteuaiz m,\nWeek\u2019s Financial High Lights\nBy the Associsted Preia. _\nThis week. Last week. Same week\u201929.\nBrokers\u2019 loans $3,345,000 $3,341,000 $5,550,000\nFederal Reserve system ratio 78.3% 76.3% 69.4%\nHoldings (United States):\nSecurities $476,536 $476,662 $201,771\nGold reserve 2,985,212 2,975,215 2,667,184\nRediscounts 406.941 433,223 820,634\nBank clearings 9,680,402 9,686,773 12,665,347\n(Final three ciphers omitted In above.)\nCarloadings week ending January 18.. 847,353 863,191 931,861\nCrude oil production (barrels) 2,615,600 2,661,650 2,663,100\nStock sales (N. Y. Stock Exchange) 18,801,830 14,241,920 25,608,150\nBond sales (N. Y. Stock Exchange).,., $49,497,000 $46,833,000 $52,414,500\nNew financing 135,769,000 113,957,000\nCall money rate 4-4%% 4-4%% 6-8%\nTime money rate 4%-5% 4%-4%% T%-7%%\nCommercial paper 4%-5% 4%-5% s'/ 4 -5%%\nWHOLESALE TRADING DECLINES\nAS RESULT OF HEAVY SNOWS\nDealers at D. C. Market Look Forward to\nClearing Weather \u2014Commodity\nReceipts Good.\nAnticipating a probable early clear\ning of snow from the city streets and\ncountry roads, which should mean a\nboosting of business, dealers in the\nwholesale district heaved a sigh of\nI relief when the week\u2019s market closed\n\u2018\u2018lt was strictly a week of unpleasant\ni weather conditions,\u201d was remarked by\na wholesaler, \u2018\u2018and such conditions were\ntrading.\nnever known to help trading.\n\u2018\u2018There are many retailers who sim\nply will not drive through snow and\nslush to make purchases unless it is\nabsolutely necessary to do so,\u201d he add\ned, \u201cprobably depending upon the sales\nof canned foods to take the place of\nuncanned commodities.\u201d\nJust what weather conditions will pre\nvail at the opening of the approaching\nweek\u2019s market is problematical. Should\nthe streets be sloppy, dealers anticipate\nquiet trading, but if the snow has\ncleared away a different condition is\nanticipated.\n\"Prompt work on the part of District\nauthorities to clear the streets of snow\nwas fully appreciated,\u201d commented a\ndealer. \u201cSimilar storms many years\nago probably would have meant an\nentirely different state of affairs.\nEffects of Storm.\n\u201cYears ago,\u201d the merchant added,\n\u201ca snowstorm of any magnitude meant\na terrible drawback to merchants, but\nwith the advent of motor trucks and\nImproved street cleaning apparatus\nthings are different, and business does\nnot suffer so much.\u201d\nOnly a slight decrease in receipts of\ncertain commodities the past few days\nresulted from the storm. Some haulers\nof poultry, eggs and farm produce from\nMaryland and Virginia, especially those\nliving far distant from State roads, and\nboulevards, were delayed or prevented\nfrom reaching here on schedule time.\n\u201cBut railroad trains and steamboats\ncontinued to run,\u201d observed a dealer,\n\u201cand the two public utilities could have\nlanded any quantity of commodities\nwanted, and on short notice.\n\u201cThe day for a storm of a few days\u2019\nduration seriously interrupting busi\nness.\u201d he added, \u201chas passed.\u201d\nWhile conditions during the week\nwere not wholly satisfactory, according\nto merchants in the wholesale district,\nthey were not wholly unsatisfactory. In\nthe commission house district the cold\nweather demanded the taking of extra\nprecautions against losses as a result of\nfreezing.\nIt became necessary for the removal\nof most supplies of fruits and vegetables\nIndoors or to places where canvas pro\ntections prevented freezing. Merchant*\nwere given such ample warning of the\napproach of the freezing weather that\nthey were able to avoid losses to any\nconsiderable extent.\nRetail Demand.\nYesterday morning there was the\nusual week end demand for commod\nities for the retail trade registered. Re\ntailers were on hand bright and early,\nsome wanting supplies for their Satur\nday breakfast trade, while others ap\npeared later in the day for supplies for\ntrade later in the day and to have\nenough left over for the beglninng of\nbusiness tomorrow.\nThere was no heavy boosting of prices\nduring the week because of the appear\nance of the snow, dealers reported,\nprices of most commodities continuing\nduring the week without much change.\nPrincipal interest, according to mer\nchants, was in the egg market. It had\nbeen expected that prices would reach\na much lower market by the close of\nthe week, but the appearance of snow\nprobably kept them as high as they\nwere reported at the close of the week\u2019s\nmarket.\n\"Prices have been due for a decided\ndrop the past month,\" was the sugges\ntion of a wholesaler, \u201cand such a drop\nis bound to come before long.\u201d\nDropping of the wholesale prices was\nfollowed by cheaper retail prices, al\nthough in some instances high prices\nfor specially selected hennery stock still\nprevail. Prices of commodities at the\nclose of the week\u2019s market were re\nported by dealers as follows:\nButter\u2014One-pound prints. 42a43;\ntub, 41a42; store packed, 25a30.\nEggs\u2014Hennery, 38a39; fresh selected,\n38a39; current receipts, 36a37.\nPoultry, alive\u2014Turkeys, young, 32a\n33; old, 27a28; Spring chickens, large,\n28a30; medium, 28a30: broilers, 32a33;\nLeghorns, 28; fowls, 28a30; roosters, 20;\nducks, 15al8. Dressed\u2014Turkeys, young,\n36a38; old, 32a33; Spring chickens, 35a\n37; broilers, 38a40; Leghorns, 36; fowls,\n30a32; roosters, 22a23; capons, 35a40;\nducks, 28a30; keats, 50a60.\nMeats, fresh killed\u2014Beef, 23a25; veal,\n28; pork loins, 28; fresh hams, 25;\nfresh shoulders, 20; smoked hams, 25a\n27; smoked shoulders, 22; bacon, 25a26;\nlard, in bulk, 12y 2 in packages, 13'/ 2\nLive stock\u2014Calves, 17; lambs, 13.\nWhile growers in Belgium, Cuba,\nCalifornia, Florida and Texas are sup\nplying quantities of fresh fruits and\nvegetables to local dealers, hot house\nproducts from States in the North and\nWest are supplying show vegetables,\nchiefly tomatoes, cucumbers and mush\nrooms. Some of the hot house plants\nfrom which supplies are being received\nare located at Terre Haute, Ind.; Ash\ntabula, Ohio; the Kenneth Square\nneighborhood of Pennsylvania and\nBoston, Mass.\n\u201cIt Is an interesting sight to visit\nany of the green houses,\u201d observed a\nlocal dealer, \u201cparticularly the one in\nTerre Haute, where cucumbers are pro\nduced in a house covering 33 acres,\nand It appears almost next to impos\nsible that the large show vegetable\ncan be raised only a few Inches from\na deep covering of snow from time to\ntime during the Winter.\u201d\nThe dealer explained how the vines\nare trained overhead, and the cucum\nbers are very large. The cucumbers\nare put through a washing before being\npacked for shipment, it is stated, to\nprevent spotting. Boxes of two dozen\nof the vegetable the past few days\nsold around $5 and $6.\nOther Vegetable Prices.\nReceipts of hot house tomatoes the\npast week have not been very heavy,\naccording to reports, as was the case\nwith the cucumbers. Mushrooms con\ntinued plentiful and cheap, however,\nreceipts having been fairly heavy most\nof the current Winter season. Yester\nday they were offered at from 85 cents\nto sl.lO a basket of three pounds.\nAnother product of the hot house\nattracting attention is rhubarb. Re\nceipts the past month, not exception\nally heavy, were reported by dealers\nas the best stock ever offered in the\nlocal market. It came in small boxes\nof approximately five pounds and found\nready sale. Small quantities of polk\nsalad, another hot house product, were\nreceived the month. waa\nported of exceptionally fine quality, but\nnot much in demand.\nFlorida and California tomatoes have\nnot been particularly plentiful the past\nmonth and many of them were small\nand not very much in demand. Prices\nwere not cheap. Lima beans, always\na good seller, were received from Flor\nida the past few days, but only in\nsmall quantities. They sold around $8\na hamper, retailers selling them at\n$1.25 a quart.\n\u201cWhen consumers are asked $1.25 for\na quart of the beans,\" observed a re\ntailer, \"they seem to think they are\nbeing robbed.\n\u201cI\u2019m willing to admit the price is\nvery high,\u201d the dealer added, \u201cbut the\nretailer very little more than breaks\neven at that price.\u201d\nStormy conditions in the Norfolk, Va.,\nneighborhood the past few dafys played\nhavoc with vegetable growers, prevent\ning the gathering of kale, spinach and\ncollards, thereby reducing receipts of\nthe vegetables in the local market.\nPeas, received from Mexico and Cali\nfornia, came in quantities large enough\nto meet the week\u2019s demands, the Cali\nfornia product bringing a dollar or two\nmore a hamper than the Mexican stock.\n\u201cThe difference in prices represents\nthe difference in quality,\" suggested a\ndealer. \"They present about the same\nsplendid appearance, but the California\nproduct is far superior to that from\nMexico.\u201d\nIncluded in the list of vegetables of\nfered the retail trade during the week\nwere onions, cabbage, celery, lettuce,\neggplant, both varieties of potatoes,\nstring beans, cauliflower, carrots, beets\nand okra.\nStrawberries, very scarce and high\nearly in the week, were received in\nlarger quantities the past two days and\nsold at lower prices. Early in the week\nthey were so scarce that a flat price of\n75 cents a quart was demanded, but in\ncreased receipts resulted in prices drop\nping to 60 and 65 cents.\nOranges and Grapefruit.\nOranges and grapefruit continued in\nmoderate receipts, pineapples appearing\nin large quantities and dealers also had\nAlligator pears in light receipt; plentiful\nsupplies of apples and cranberries and\ngrapes and pears in quantities sufficient\nto meet demands.\nStormy weather the past week af\nfected business at Municipal Fish Mar\nket and scattered wholesale dealers in\nmarine products. Dealers had fairly\nlarge quantities of fresh fish and plenti\nful supplies of frozen fish to meet de\nmands of retailers. They also had\noysters in quantities sufficiently large to\nmeet demands.\n\"In other words,\u201d remarked a dealer,\n\u201cpatrons of the Municipal Fish Market\nwere able to get all that was necessary\nto supply their wants.\u201d\nTurkey receipts continue fairly heavy,\nraisers, it is stated, shipping stock held\nback from the Christmas holiday sea\nson for higher prices. A fairly good\ndemand for the turkeys were registered\nthroughout the week, dealers reported,\nand prices were what dealers termed\nreasonable to cheap.\nOther varieties of poultry also were\nreceived in quantities sufficiently heavy\nto meet demands, although they did not\ncontinue quite so heavy during the short\nstoimy period. Eggs also continued in\nfairly heavy receipts, prices not being\nvery much affected by the storm.\nFruit and Vegetable Review.\nYesterday\u2019s daily market report on\nfruit* and vegetables (compiled by the\nMarket News Service, Bureau of Agri\ncultural Economics) said:\nApples\u2014Supplies moderate; demand\n(Continued on Seventh Page!)\nSTEEfoPERAfiONS\nSHOW BIG ADVANCE\nPlants in Various Sections Resume\nActivity\u2014Buying Orders\nAre Heavy.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nCLEVELAND,' February 1 \u2014Steel\nworks operations have expanded for the\nfourth consecutive week since the turn\nof the year, now approximating 75 per\ncent, or within 10 points of last Janu\nary, says Iron Trade Review, Cleveland\nBecause the month opened inauspi\nclously January production statistics\nwill not adequately gage current activi\nty, but increasingly is it evident that\nthe iron and steel industry 1* working\nup to its usual production peak in\nMarch-Aprll.\nAutomotive requirements, while spotty\nare enlarging rapidly, with a year not\nfar behind 1929 now in prospect. Pro\nducers of railroad track material al\nready are at a 90 per cent gait. Car\nbuilders\u2019 specifications practically match\nlast year\u2019s. Building steel needs, espe\ncially for bridges, are opening up. Os\nmajor outlets for finished steel only\npipe fails to participate in general im\nprovement.\nAs demand broadens, producers are\nintensifying their efforts to get the\nprice situation in hand. Seml-flnished\nsteel, cold finished steel bars, rail steel\nand hot strip are off and pig iron is\nunder pressure, but further attempts to\nbreak bars, plates and shapes have been\nresisted. In some flat rolled steel lines\nprices have receded to the point where\nreduction in wages is threatened in\nmills whose union scale is based upon\nsales prices, but the industry is bent on\nmaintaining wages.\nAnother big week In railroad buying\nhas been recorded. Chesapeake Sc Ohio\nand affiliated lines, having awarded 105\nlocomotives and 55 separate tenders are\nto close shortly on 11,350 freight cars.\nChicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul Sc Pa\ncific has placed 2,300 freight cars and\nhas 750 on inquiry. Louisville Sc Nash\nville is out for 1,800, while the Beaboard\nAir Line has doubled Its inquiry for\n1,000. Miscellaneous car awards the\npast week totaled 308. Additional rails\nare being distributed by the New York\nCentral.\nTwo subway sections at New York re\nquire 18,000 tons of structural material\nBids are in at Pittsburgh on a bridge\ntaking 12,000 tons, while two contem\nplated bridges at Buffalo are estimated\nat 18,000 tons. A river tunnel at New\nYork calls for 36,000 tons of cast iron\nplate sections.\nSteelmaking operations are up 5\npoints at Chicago, to 80 per cent. Since\nJanuary 1 four blast furnaces have been\nadded there. Pittsburgh mills are up\nslightly, to Just above 70 per cent, with\nYoungstown at 72, Birmingham 75 and\nBuffalo off a trifle to 55. Steel Corpo\nration subsidiaries this week are at 75\n\u2019flil MBA MRifilfr fiflE MBtlMfc MtL\nSTOCKS DISCOUNT\nGAINSININDUSTRY\nMarket Stages Broad Recov\nery During Week as Trade\nConditions Improve.\nBY CHARLES F. SPEARE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, February I.\u2014Whether\nbusiness has improved on the heels of a\nrising stock market, or whether stocks\nhave advanced in sympathy with more\nfavorable reports from the industrial\nworld is not so important as the fact\nthat both trade and securities this week\nhave shown positive recovery.\nIndividual stocks must still go up\nconsiderably to gather in the slack in\nprices that occurred during December.\nOn the average, however, industrial is\nsues on Friday advanced through the\nhigh average of December 9, which is\nof Importance in a technical interpre\ntation of the stock market\u2019s trend.\nThe week has witnessed not only bet\nter prices for stocks, but a volume of\ntrading that would have been consid\nered most satisfactory to commission\nhouses two and three years ago. One\nafter another of the important share\ngroups have been supported and pro\nmoted, such as the steels, copper,\nmotors, public utilities, electrical manu\nfacturing and even the indifferent\noils. Out of this has come a recov\nery which amounts to an average of\nnearly 70 points in the Industrial and\npublic utility divisions of the market,\ncompared with the minimum prices of\nlast November. Put in another form,\nthis is to say that whereas these stocks\nwere off an average of 50 per cent last\nAutumn from their high prices of the\nyear, the shrinkage from that level\ntoday is only 30 per cent.\nSteel Earnings Encouraging.\nThere have been a number of de\nvelopments to which the stock market\ncould not fall to give respectful atten\ntion. The one that had most im\nmediate effect was the annual report\nof the United States Steel Corpora\ntion, which Included those weeks in\n1929 when the iron and steel industry\nwas at the lowest ebb since 1922. Ob\nviously, the momentum of earlier\nmonths had much to do with the sur\nprising results shown by this company\nin the December quarter, and if the\nprecedent* of other years are worth\nanything as a guide, the March quar\nter, in which the steel industry is hav\ning a rapid comeback, will be less\nfavorable than that Just presented.\nHowever, earning three times its cur\nrent dividend rate of $7 a share on\nits common stock, which supplements\nequaUy good statement of the\nBethlehem Steel Corporation, the United\nStates Steel Corporation continues to\nshow the vitality that has attracted so\nmany hundreds of thousands of in\nvestors to it* securities. As an indi\ncation that the steel industry is far\nfrom sick, one independent producer\nre-established the dividend on its\nstock and another increased it* rate\nduring the week.\nEncouragement has been given by\nthe advices from Washington on the\ngaJ fl, 111 e \u00bbPloyment, which means\nnothing more than that industry is\npicking up; by the ability of the cop\nper producers to maintain an 18-cent\nrate for metal though other commodi\nties are falling; by the sharp contrac\ntion in crude oil production, and by\nthe evidence of more active buying in\nthe automobile industry, as well as by\nagencies identified with the construc\ntion of buildings and of ships.\nMoney Situation Favorable.\nQuite as fundamental in their value\n..*f^ rltles m the expanding trade\nindications are those that have ap\npeared this week in the money mar\nkets of the world. For the first time\nin two yeftrs call loans on EYid&y were\nf\u201d\\e w ed at 4 per cent, which is of\nar S^ m nce the r *te was\nestablished at the month end, when\ndemands normally are on a rising\nscale. Bankers\u2019 acceptances also have\nbeen lowered. The position of the Fed\nsteadily grows better as\nmember banks reduce their borrowings,\nwhich are now 65 per cent less than\nthey were at the peak in 1929 and\nth? they have In\nthe last three years.\nere If *n insistent demand in some\nquarters for a reduction in the Federal\nReserve rediscount rate in New York to\n4 per cent. If business is to go on ex\npanding, such a policy would not be\njustified.\nThe reduction in loans on securities\ncontinues at a substantial weekly pace\nbeing helped along by rising prices for\nstocks which permit borrower and lend\ner to cancel their contracts to mutual\nadvantage. There Is still, however, a\npeat mass of unmarketable securities\nin the portfolio of the banks through\nout the country. One of the explana\ntions of the weakness in prices of grain\nand cotton is that interior banks have\nbeen trying to improve their condition\nthrough liquidation of commodities for\nwhich there was a ready market com\npared with the \u201cfrozen\u201d condition of\nloana on securities.\nWeakness in Commodities.\nThe situation in commodities is un\nsatisfactory. Temporarily, there has\nbeen a slight recovery in the commodity\nindex. Conspicuous weakness, however,\nhas developed in many quarters out of\noverproduction and a falling off in both\ndomestic and foreign demand for manu\nfactured goods. The condition in wheat\nand in other farm products, as well as in\ncotton, has attracted attention in Wall\nstreet this week by reason of its eco\nnomic significance and its possible po\nlitical reactions. If this were a presi\ndential year there would obviously be\nmuch political agitation and argument\nbased on the poor performance of the\nmajor farm staples. This might lead to\na reopening of the war policy of price\nfixing. A collateral feature of falling\nprices of farm products is the bearing\nthis may have on railroad rates in the\nmodern congressional adaptation of\nrates to the going prices for such prod\nucts.\nThe railroads, always sensitive to in\ndustrial currents, had a poor month in\nNovember, a poorer one in December,\nand, Judging from the carloading fig\nures, their earnings were still running\noff in January. This would explain to\nsome extent the relatively small recov\nery in the prices of railroad stocks to\nthat which has taken place in public\nutility and industrial Issues.\nIn all, however, 1929 was one of the\nbeat years in the history of the Amer\nican carriers. Never were they so effi\nciently administered with a ratio of\noperating expenses to gross earning of\n71.4 per cent, which the director of\nthe Bureau of Railway Economics states\nis the lowest since 1917, and with a re\nturn bn property investment, in spite\nof the decreases of November and De\ncember, of nearly 5 per gvit compared\nwith less than 4% par esni in 1928 and\nabout the same as in 19'' ;\u2014the banner\nyear following Govetament control.\nIn the field of international finance\nthe striking event this week was the\nreduction to 3 per cent in the redis\ncount rate of the Bank of France. This\nhad to come soon, but was put forward\nearlier than anticipated as a measure\nto prevent a further movement of gold\ninto the already overflowing vaults of\nthe French bank. The present rate is\nlower than any now quoted by the cen\ntral banks of Europe and gives France\na position of pre-eminence in the\nfinancing of the world's capital require\nments.\nThe reduction is likely to be followed\nin the coming weeks by other banks on\nthe continent and by the Bank of Eng\nland. Out of this cheaper period in\nmoney rates there should come greater\nIndustrial activity and also the ability\nto buy goods in the American market.\nAs yet there has been no pronounced\neffect, rather a disappointing sequel, to\n\u00abmlm mean atm Imm m ttm Abml*\nI FINANCIAL I\nAgain Heads Bank\nWjM h jwn\nfjafcfT\nHyp m I^H\nm\nJOHN B. LARNER\nWu imoni the Washington financiers\nreturned to office at the recent annua!\nmeetings. As head of the Washington\nLoan A Trust Co. for many years, he\nhas made a brilliant financial record.\nHe is a director In other corporations\nand closely connected with many im\nportant civic Interests.\nRETURN OF PUBLIC\"\nTO MARKET IS SEEN\nBroker\u2019s Review Finds Ample\nBuying Power Indicated in\nMonth\u2019s Activities.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, February I.\u2014The fact\nthat values have been able to present\nsuch a firm front, In the face of reali\nzation by bankers and others, indicates\nthe existence of ample buying power,\nsays Henry Clews Co. The month of\nJanuary has witnessed the disposal of\nnearly $400,000,000 of new issues, and\nthis taken in conjunction with an esti\nmated reduction of holdings by banks\nin the sum, of $250,000,000, shows that\nthe capacity of individuals and invest\nment institutions to absorb securities is\nvery satisfactory. The question how far\nbanks will continue a process of liqui\ndation, of course, remains to be an\nswered, but it is entirely possible that\nthe sales of securities which they have\ncarried on during the month of Janu\nary will not go very much further, de\npending upon the actual condition of\nthe institutions and the extent to which\ntheir business customers call upon them\nfor commercial accommodation. With\nthe Federal Reserve system freely ab\nsorbing Government obligations and re\nleasing credit when needed, at very\nmoderate rates, there need be no doubt\nthat any further liquidation will be\nlimited to actual requirements. Failure\nto reduce the Bank of England rate has\nbeen due, it is believed, entirely to the\nrecently rather softer tendency of\nsterling, which has deferred the ex\npected action. In the opinion of local\nbanking authorities, there is no reason\nwhy the reduction in the reserve rate\nwhich has been expected for some time\npast should be made to wait upon action\nin Great Britain, and a lowering of it\nis accordingly thought likely as a factor\nin the early future.\nMergers and Readjustments.\nAnnouncement of the terms of the\nlarge steel merger which has been pro\nvided for, through the consolidation of\nthe Republic Iron Sc Steel Co., the Cen\ntral Alloy Steel Corporation, Doner\nSteel Co. and others, brings to a close\nnegotiations which have been in prog\nress for some time, and holds out to\nstockholders the prospect of a profitable\nexchange of securities. Other consoli\ndations and exchanges are also under\nway, among those pending being the\noffer made by United Gas to exchange\nits stock for Southern Gas, while Tide\nwater Associated Oil has renewed its\noffer for the stock of Associated Oil,\ngood during the present month. Nego\ntiations for the accomplishment of\nother mergers and consolidations are\nunder way, and it is likely that as a\nresult of the rearrangements growing\nout of them, various issues will assume\na different position in the open market.\nThe prospective settlement of the major\ntroubles of the film industry through\nan agreement between the conflicting\ninterests, centering around the Fox Film\nCorporation, is also believed likely to\navoid possible embarrassments in other\nbranches of the same group, and con\nsequently to confirm all classes of good\nshares in that division In the position\nthey now occupy. Weaker units are\nexpected to have the opportunity of\nconsolidating with the stronger upon\nterms which may prove advantageous\nby putting various issues upon a basis\nmore assured than that wnich they have\noccupied heretofore. All this process\nof rearrangement and readjustment is\nlaying the foundation of a very much\nmore vigorous and satisfactory market\nfor coming months, and is to be re\ngarded as a piece of foundation work\nessential to the rebuilding of satisfac\ntory conditions.\nMarket Review and Outlook.\nUnquestionably there Is an Increase\nof public interest in the stock market\nand in investment conditions generally.\ntendency toward stronger prices\nwhich has of late made itself felt is\nresponsible for some part of this growth.\nWhat has operated more to hold back\nactivity than anything else, has doubt\nless been the fact that many persons\nhave questioned the extent of imme\ndiate prospect for appreciation. The\noptimistic view that is being taken by\ncapable authorities with reference to\nthe business outlook should dispel this\nattitude of mind, and it should be re\nmembered that, taking the market as\na whole, the opportunities to buy which\nnow present themselves are not likely\nto be repeated. While it la quite pos\nsible profit-taking sales may be en\ncountered now and then, this is not a\nsituation to be regarded seriously; in\ndeed, it would be easy to lose, as a\npermanency, the openings which now\npresent themselves in many branches\nof the investment field by holding off\ntoo long and displaying an over-cautious\nattitude.\nBUY CITY BOHDS.\nRICHMOND, Va., February 1 (Spe\ncial). \u2014The Chase Securities Corpora\ntion of New York and the State-Plant\ners\u2019 Bank Sc Trust Co. of Richmond.\nVa.. have purchased $675,000 city of\nCharlottesville, Va., bonds, which will\nbe offered to the investing public with\nin a few days, it has been announced\nhere.\nThe bonds yield 4.75 per cent and\nmaturities of the bonds range from 1\nto 40 years. They are general improve\nment bonds.\ncan bond market, where there Is in\nprogress an active shifting from low In\ncome-producing securities, such as gov\nernments and \"legals,\u201d into the newer\nmortgages and debentures brought out\n\"under the market\" rather than above\nit, as was the case in 1928. This will\ncorrect Itself in time, depending on the\ndegree to which the new offerings are\nregulated to the capacity of the market\nto absorb them.\nMmWMMU ai.-b.JLf\nRESTRICTION IN OIL\nPRODUCTION URGED\nFurther Conservation of Out\nput Declared Necessary\nas Industry Aid.\nBT JOHN F. SINCLAIR.\nSpccisl Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, February I.\u2014\u201cTo clear\nup the situation In the oil Industry,\nmore drastic restrictive measures in the\noil fields must be worked out this year,\neither voluntarily or arbitrarily,\u201d said\nan oil leader in New York this week.\nThe year 1929 broke the record in\nthat the production of crude oil in the\nUnited States for the first time in\nhistory surpassed 1,000,000,000 barrels\u2014\n-12 per cent more than the 1928 record.\nThis in spite of the fact that some\n10,000,000 barrels of crude oil was\nshut in by different proration agree\nments.\nWorld oil production in 1929 was\n1,460,000,000 barrels. So the United\ni States produced more than two-thirds\nI of the world total.\ni The year closed with total oil stocks\non hand of 530,000,000 barrels\u2014a new\nhigh record. Sufficient to supply\ni American requirements for seven or\neight months.\nSo today, the United States, produc\ning 2,600,000 barrels dally, is far in\nthe lead in oil production, followed by\nVenezuela, Russia, Persia, Mexico,\nRumania, Dutch East Indies, Colombia\nand Peru, in the order named.\nVenezuela, second on the list, has a\nproduction of but 13 per cent of that\nI of the United States.\nLabor and Management,\nJust before Thomas E. Mitten, the\n?reat Philadelphia transportation genius,\nwas drowned a few months ago on his\nestate near Philadelphia, he declared\nthat the huge industrial units in the\nmaking were in danger of losing their\nconception of the labor problem as\nactive management is further removed\nfrom the worker.\nSaid Mr. Mitten:\n\"I\u2014We must give the worker a full\nvoice, equal to that of the manage\nment, in all matters that affect his\nwages and working conditions.\n\u201c2 \u2014We must give the worker as\nsurance of a fair rate in wages, and\nalso added reward in accordance with\nthe success of his efforts.\n\"3. We must see that the worker is\ngiven full opportunity to invest his own\ncapital in the workshop in which he\nr earns his dally bread, and see to it that\nj this investment is of such a nature\nthat will give the worker so great an\ninfluence in management that Amer\nican industry will always be assured of\nmanagement in sympathy with labor.\u201d\ni Since his death, the principles which\nhe laid down have been continued by\na loyal staff, built up during his active\nbusiness career.\nSprague\u2019s Appointment.\n\"Why go outside Great Britain for\nbanking experts?\u201d ask leading British\nnewspapers of the powerful Bank of\nEngland.\nThe recent appointment of Prof. O.\nM. W. Sprague of Harvard as economic\nadvisor to the Bank of England to\nreplace a much younger American,\nWalter Stewart, 44, who has been acting\nin that capacity for the past two years,\n1* characterized by one London paper\n\"as an unpleasant shock.\u201d For cen\nturles the British have been the in\ntemational bankers. Their word has\n1 3 eei law 111 the field of international\nbanking.\nBut with the rapid rise of the United\nStates as the greatest of world creditor\npowers a new situation has developed.\nThe Bank of England, ably managed,\nknows banking talent, whether it hap\npens to be English or American\nThe appointment of the American\nProf. Sprague, to the staff of the\nof England should be a cause for real\ncongratulations, because he is consld\n-1 ered by those who know as among the\nhalf dozen ablest banking economists in\nthe world.\nEvening Schools.\nWhen people talk about New York\nbeing pleasure mad, they often forget\nthat there are more students attending\nevening school in New York every night\nthan there are people who attend thea\nters. The average attendance In the\nj theaters is approximately 100,000 a\nnight; in the schools. 140,000.\nWhat is the meridian age for achieve\ni ment? Prof. Thorndike, noted psychol\nogist, found by examining a group of I\nsuccessful men that 45 for scientists\n1 and 51 for men of business are the\ni prime ages for achievement.\nThe New York Central Railroad\nwhen it changed over from steam to\nelectrified engines, did not replace the\nold engineers by electrical engineers. I\nbut taught the old engineers to run the\ni newer type of motor-propelled trains.\n\"Cato mastered Greek at 65.\u201d says\nThorndike. \"George F. Baker, at 88, is\n1 a business giant today.\u201d\n\"It\u2019s not the number of years, but I\nthe burning fire within each individual\nthat matters.\u201d\nAgricnltaral Exports.\nOne of America\u2019s bright spots at the\nmoment is the export of agricultural g\nimplements. The latest figures, those\nof December, show an Increase of aU\nmost $3,000,000 over the exports of De\ncember, 1928. Then they amounted to\n$9,426,000, while this last December\nthey totaled $12,273,000.\nTractors were largely the cause of\nthe Increase.\nEurope, with her credit easing, turns\nmore and more to machinery to do her\nwork. Its only a matter of time when S\nher industrial machinery will be mod\nernized as it is in the United States\nand Canada.\nThen will come the real contest for\nforeign trade.\nHonduras\u2019 Business Depression.\nHonduras, which specializes largely in\ncoffee and bananas, suffered from a\nslight business depression during last\nyear. Late reports show that during\n1929 Honduras exported 28,241,000\nbunches of bananas, compared with 27,-\n462,000 bunches in 1928, although dur\ning the month of December the total\nexport amounted to 2,059,000 bunches,\nas compared with 1,544,000 bunches in\nthe same month of 1928.\nThe coming coffee crop of Honduras\nis reported to be good; but with low\nprices, advances and credits have been\ngreatly restricted.\nThis Picture Indicates about the gen- S\u2019\neral trend of business throughout South\nAmerica.\n(Coprrtsht. 1910. by North American Newt- H\npaper Alliance.)\nTELEPHONE COMPANY\nREPORTS ON REVENUES\nThe Chesapeake Potomac Tele- I\nphone Co. of Baltimore City expended\n$4,602,647 for new outside plant and\ncentral office equipment in Maryland\nduring 1929. Retirements during this\nperiod were $2,230,356. making net ad\nditions $2,372,291.\nTelephone operating revenues for the\nyear, as shown on the report of opera\ntions Just filed with the Public Service\nCommission, were $13,665,375. Expenses\nduring this period were $10,761,139.\nmaking net revenues $2,904,236, which\nis equivalent to 6.67 per cent on the\naverage value of the company\u2019s prop-#\nCHICAGO DAIRY MARKET.\nCH ?CAGO, February 1 (A*).\u2014Butter\u2014\nUnsettled: receipts, 11,581 tubs; cream\nery. extras, 35%; standards, 35%; ex-\ntra firsts. 34% to 36; firsts, 33 to 34;\nseconds, 31 to 32.\nEggs\u2014Steady: receipts, 7,146 cases;\naufclaSttMNsaMk&i 35 to I","height":"25584","width":"19809"}}
